<TITLE> Power situation will return to normal by Nov 30: spokesman </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 18 (bdnews24.com)  The power situation jeopardised by cyclone Sidr will return to normal by Nov 30, an official said Sunday. "Work is underway to resume power at the field level. On Sunday demand for power was 3,350 megawatts whereas the production was 3,219 megawatts," the chief adviser's press secretary Syed Fahim Munaim said in a press briefing after a cabinet meeting. The government formed a committee to investigate the cause of the collapse of the national grid twice on Nov 16 in the wake of the rampaging cyclone. Former Bangladesh Power Development Board chairman and former managing director of Power Grid Company of Bangladesh ANM Rizwan was named the convener of the seven-member committee, Munaim said. The committee has been set the deadline to submit its report in two weeks. The committee will also suggest ways to avoid grid failures and make recommendations for sound operations in future. Munaim said the chief adviser had asked the finance adviser to speak to the Bangladesh Bank governor about disbursing agriculture loans to farmers. The advisers sought permission from the chief adviser to visit the cyclone-battered areas. They plan to visit the affected areas, starting Monday. The meeting held at the Chief Adviser's Office also focused on the progress of relief and rescue operations and other activities of the ministries of food and disaster management, communications and posts and telecommunications. Attending the meeting, the post and telecommunications secretary told the chief adviser that satellite phones had been installed in Barguna, Amtoli, Dublar Char, Kalapara, Mothbaria, Bhandaria and Kathalia. The communications secretary said 18 ferries had been damaged in the cyclone. Six had resumed services and the remaining 12 would be ready for services in a week or two. The food and disaster management secretary said that 4,092 tonnes of rice and 10,000 blankets had so far been distributed. bdnews24.
